&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.050 --> 00:00:24.350
&gt;&gt; Fenella France:
I'm Fenella France,

00:00:24.350 --> 00:00:26.540
chief of Preservation Research
and Testing Division and I want

00:00:26.540 --> 00:00:31.580
to welcome you to this series of
one of our talks presentations.

00:00:31.580 --> 00:00:33.980
We are absolutely
delighted today to be able

00:00:33.980 --> 00:00:35.410
to introduce Randy Silverman,

00:00:35.410 --> 00:00:37.920
who is well known
to many of you.

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:40.740
Randy served as the head of
preservation at the University

00:00:40.740 --> 00:00:43.780
of Utah Marriott
Library since 1993.

00:00:43.780 --> 00:00:47.040
He teaches workshops on disaster
planning for the Western States

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:50.680
and Territories Preservation
Assistance Service WSTPAS

00:00:50.680 --> 00:00:52.670
and is recognized for
his national disaster

00:00:52.670 --> 00:00:53.970
recovery efforts.

00:00:53.970 --> 00:00:56.110
He has 80 professional
publications

00:00:56.110 --> 00:00:58.460
and has presented professional
lectures or workshops

00:00:58.460 --> 00:01:01.760
in 30 states and 13
foreign countries,

00:01:01.760 --> 00:01:03.400
we'll ask for a list later.

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:07.890
He was given the American
Library Association Banks Harris

00:01:07.890 --> 00:01:10.660
Preservation award in 2013,

00:01:10.660 --> 00:01:13.980
received a Fulbright
specialist award in 2014,

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:16.890
and was awarded the Utah
Academy of Sciences,

00:01:16.890 --> 00:01:18.590
Arts and Letters Gardner prize

00:01:18.590 --> 00:01:22.960
for outstanding academic
contributions in 2016.

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:24.950
When I spoke with Randy last
year and we were starting

00:01:24.950 --> 00:01:26.900
to talk about some
collaborative research

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:28.200
and he mentioned this project.

00:01:28.200 --> 00:01:31.070
And we were talking about you
know some of the challenges

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:32.730
with some of these
larger projects

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:34.850
and he very graciously
agreed to come

00:01:34.850 --> 00:01:36.310
and talk with us about this.

00:01:36.310 --> 00:01:40.130
So, his presentation today is
a mold outbreak in Tbilisi,

00:01:40.130 --> 00:01:42.850
Georgia, technical and
interpersonal challenges

00:01:42.850 --> 00:01:46.510
and please help me
welcome him today.

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:51.500
[ Applause ]

