00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:14.180
thank you very much
for your service.

00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:18.200
I first met Zurab who's
the library director

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:20.200
at the University of Tbilisi

00:03:20.200 --> 00:03:25.260
on a US State Department
familiarization tour in 2013.

00:03:25.260 --> 00:03:28.660
He and other Georgian library
directors toured the University

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:30.320
of Utah's Marriott Library

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:35.170
and when I showed him our
conservation lab he asked me

00:03:35.170 --> 00:03:36.540
questions about mold

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:40.180
and I didn't know then what
he was really talking about.

00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:42.520
But two years later when
this picture appeared

00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:46.870
in the New York Times captioned
zoo animals on the loose

00:03:46.870 --> 00:03:51.360
in Tbilisi after
flooding I was concerned

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:53.270
and so I contacted
the library to find

00:03:53.270 --> 00:03:56.750
out if the flood
had affected them.

00:03:56.750 --> 00:03:59.480
And while the collection
was unharmed

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:03.130
by that flood this mold
problem was still going on

00:04:03.130 --> 00:04:05.940
and it was still a big issue.

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:11.180
So, the Blue Shield of Georgia
identified grant possibilities

00:04:11.180 --> 00:04:14.960
and along with the library's
conservation department

00:04:14.960 --> 00:04:18.890
at the university wrote a
cultural heritage emergency

00:04:18.890 --> 00:04:23.340
stabilization grant to the
Prince Claus Fund in Amsterdam.

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:25.790
And the first grant was
not successful, but a year

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:29.030
and a half later the
second one [audio cuts].

00:04:29.030 --> 00:04:34.440
So, I arrived in Tbilisi
on January 27th, 2017,

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:38.180
which is like a year
ago for a 10-day visit

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:41.030
and my hosts were Menana
[phonetic] who is pictured

00:04:41.030 --> 00:04:46.010
on your left and who is the
head of Blue Shield and Marie

00:04:46.010 --> 00:04:47.540
who is the paper conservator

00:04:47.540 --> 00:04:51.380
at Tbilisi State
University Library.

00:04:51.380 --> 00:04:54.930
Georgia for I had weak
geography as a child,

00:04:54.930 --> 00:04:59.830
so I'm always curious like
on a map falls under Russia

00:04:59.830 --> 00:05:03.600
and is situated near
Turkey and Armenia.

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:07.480
And I mention for the
people viewing from Georgia

00:05:07.480 --> 00:05:12.240
that those striped areas
are the territories

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:17.030
that were lost during the
2008 Russo Georgian war,

00:05:17.030 --> 00:05:19.760
that war lasted five days,

00:05:19.760 --> 00:05:24.830
and the occupation still
affects 20% of the country.

00:05:24.830 --> 00:05:28.070
When I first arrived,
it had snowed in Tbilisi

00:05:28.070 --> 00:05:30.120
which is unusual
for them and coming

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:32.770
from Florida I thought
it was great to see snow

00:05:32.770 --> 00:05:35.100
on the palms, this is unusual.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:37.310
I was also able to see some

00:05:37.310 --> 00:05:39.000
of their wonderful
historic buildings

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.160
like this 12th century
Orthodox Church

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:45.780
and these 19th century
hot baths,

00:05:45.780 --> 00:05:48.830
which is kind of
a wonderful thing.

00:05:48.830 --> 00:05:52.820
And there were carts in the
streets selling colorful spices

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:56.360
and churchkhela which are
traditional homemade Georgian

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:58.720
candle-shaped candies.

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:02.100
It's a really great place,
you should go see it.

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:05.690
So, the main library at Tbilisi
State University was built

00:06:05.690 --> 00:06:09.250
in 1987 and it was out
at the edge of town.

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:13.720
This is a part of the
city that was new in 1987

00:06:13.720 --> 00:06:15.560
and it was anticipated to grow,

00:06:15.560 --> 00:06:18.490
but the growth never
materialized after the collapse

00:06:18.490 --> 00:06:22.620
of the Soviet Union
December of 1991.

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:27.400
So, there was a persistent
lack of maintenance money

00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:29.820
and that's left this
30-year-old building which is

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:33.840
about 400,000 square
feet largely unheated

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:35.370
and very run down.

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:42.610
In this slide the yellow
parts are the rooms

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:45.500
where the rare books are
stored, the top one is

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:47.950
on the first floor belowground

00:06:47.950 --> 00:06:52.230
and the other one is the
second floor above that,

00:06:52.230 --> 00:06:54.170
but it's still belowground.

00:06:54.170 --> 00:06:57.630
And there's actually another
room on the second floor sort

00:06:57.630 --> 00:07:01.270
of toward the core of the
building, I'm pointing for those

00:07:01.270 --> 00:07:05.970
of you at home, I don't
know if you can see that.

00:07:05.970 --> 00:07:08.970
So, those rooms were used
for storing rare books

00:07:08.970 --> 00:07:12.970
for a very long time and
they were the problem.

00:07:12.970 --> 00:07:16.580
So, we suited up to
go see the rare books.

00:07:16.580 --> 00:07:21.390
The young woman who's
holding the key was not amused

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:24.180
by our use of personal
protection equipment she thought

00:07:24.180 --> 00:07:27.740
it was weird and was kind of
put out that it took us so long

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:29.730
to prepare to enter this space.

00:07:29.730 --> 00:07:32.690
She's waiting tapping
her foot you know.

00:07:32.690 --> 00:07:35.520
Notice that at the base
of the walls there's signs

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:38.120
of moisture damage, that
was prevalent throughout

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:39.420
the building.

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:40.880
So, I would constantly see signs

00:07:40.880 --> 00:07:43.410
that there had been
water damage over time.

00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:47.320
So, we entered this space and
it's kind of dark and mysterious

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:53.920
and inside we found 80,000
rare books and that's 80,000

00:07:53.920 --> 00:07:57.280
in these multiple rooms,
that were stolen from Germany

00:07:57.280 --> 00:08:01.710
by the retreating Soviet Army
at the end of World War II.

00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:06.180
So, in the 1970's Germany
asked for the books back

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:09.060
and they were stored at
two places in Georgia

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:11.240
and the other library
gave their books back,

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:12.810
they were happy to do it.

00:08:12.810 --> 00:08:14.110
However, the University

00:08:14.110 --> 00:08:16.520
of Tbilisi's books
were badly molded.

00:08:16.520 --> 00:08:19.810
And so, Germany really wanted
to help, so they offered

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:22.750
to come there and they reviewed
the problem several times

00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:24.730
and finally said you
know it would be easier

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:27.950
to bring the books to
Germany and treat the problem

00:08:27.950 --> 00:08:30.540
where we have a lot of
equipment and facilities.

00:08:30.540 --> 00:08:33.140
And so, they ran with
that idea for a while,

00:08:33.140 --> 00:08:36.990
but there was a glitch because
shipping cultural property

00:08:36.990 --> 00:08:40.110
out of Georgia is against
the law, so then they had

00:08:40.110 --> 00:08:42.640
to change the law
to be able to do

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:45.190
that even though the
books belonged to Germany.

00:08:45.190 --> 00:08:48.000
And eventually, it just
took years and after

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:53.290
like a decade Germany said we
actually, we don't care anymore,

00:08:53.290 --> 00:08:56.140
we relinquish our hold

00:08:56.140 --> 00:08:59.270
on the books they're
yours, have a nice day.

00:08:59.270 --> 00:09:03.180
So, they now legally belong
to Tbilisi State University

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:06.330
and they're in good shape
when you open the book.

00:09:06.330 --> 00:09:09.520
You know they're rare
European imprints

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:13.280
and the paper quality looks
great, there's no problem

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:15.410
until you see the outside.

00:09:15.410 --> 00:09:19.450
And the outside was coated
with a thick layer of mold

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:23.370
and the molds changed,
there was different types,

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:26.950
there's dark molds and
light molds and a kind

00:09:26.950 --> 00:09:32.260
of patterny [phonetic] mold,
molds like you've never seen.

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:35.390
In fact, I was speaking
with people at the Centers

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:39.310
for Disease Control in the
US and they halfhearted,

00:09:39.310 --> 00:09:42.280
it was half serious in their
jokes saying you know it's a

00:09:42.280 --> 00:09:44.860
shame to destroy
such a rare example

00:09:44.860 --> 00:09:51.530
of a mature mold
ecosystem and it was.

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:53.580
They were really interesting.

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:59.020
And in fact, so I'm
there in in January

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:01.380
and this is a largely
unheated building,

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:05.420
it was freezing cold everywhere
except for a few offices.

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:09.660
But I was surprised to see
that this ancient stand

00:10:09.660 --> 00:10:15.030
of old growth mold was dry
and powdery to the touch

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:18.830
in some cases, you could
just like push it away.

00:10:18.830 --> 00:10:22.350
So, it seemed to me
on first observation

00:10:22.350 --> 00:10:27.500
that it's actually growing
and thriving in the summer

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:30.770
and hibernating in the winter
and I didn't know mold did that,

00:10:30.770 --> 00:10:34.560
so that was interesting to see.

00:10:34.560 --> 00:10:37.750
So, we started looking for
the source of the water

00:10:37.750 --> 00:10:42.550
and that orange stripe
represents a 12-inch city

00:10:42.550 --> 00:10:45.260
watermain that's running
underneath the street

00:10:45.260 --> 00:10:47.390
and parallel to the library

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:50.770
that has been leaking
apparently for years.

00:10:50.770 --> 00:10:54.520
And the university claims that
the city water department needs

00:10:54.520 --> 00:10:57.260
to repair their leaking
pipe, that's how it's done

00:10:57.260 --> 00:10:59.120
in Utah at home right.

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:02.160
But the city takes the position
that the pipe is running

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:05.480
through university property and
so it's the university's problem

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:07.360
and there's been a standoff.

00:11:07.360 --> 00:11:10.590
So, the willingness
to ignore a problem

00:11:10.590 --> 00:11:13.410
that was actually causing
standing water in the library

00:11:13.410 --> 00:11:17.780
at some points made me realize
that the lack of resources was

00:11:17.780 --> 00:11:22.630
so serious for everyone that
not dealing with problems

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:25.650
like this is what
you have to do,

00:11:25.650 --> 00:11:30.240
so that's still taking some
adjustment I have to say.

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:32.950
So, we examined the
building from the basement

00:11:32.950 --> 00:11:36.390
to the rooftop looking
for water sources.

00:11:36.390 --> 00:11:39.520
Don't you love it I'm in a
basement with my suit on,

00:11:39.520 --> 00:11:42.890
this is typical for
tourists right.

00:11:42.890 --> 00:11:47.450
And we used a moisture meter,
which is a really great tool

00:11:47.450 --> 00:11:48.750
for defining whether

00:11:48.750 --> 00:11:51.610
or not there is water
active in the walls.

00:11:51.610 --> 00:11:52.910
So, some of the damage

00:11:52.910 --> 00:11:55.840
in the walls would not set
off the moisture meter,

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:59.640
it was just old damage as
opposed to actively being wet

00:11:59.640 --> 00:12:02.460
and in some places, there
was active mold growing

00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:05.150
which was you know
a little weird.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:08.870
And interestingly,
what we were looking

00:12:08.870 --> 00:12:13.070
for originally was the source
of water coming from the street,

00:12:13.070 --> 00:12:15.890
from that you know because all
the mold damage seemed to be

00:12:15.890 --> 00:12:18.860
in those rooms that were on
that side of the building except

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:20.410
for that other room
that I mentioned,

00:12:20.410 --> 00:12:22.690
which is in the core
of the building.

00:12:22.690 --> 00:12:24.640
And so, it seemed suspicious

00:12:24.640 --> 00:12:26.580
that the water could reach
the middle of the building

00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:28.880
without having a central source.

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:34.770
So, we checked inside the
plumbing chase for the building

00:12:34.770 --> 00:12:37.880
which runs parallel to
the stairs, so going up

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:41.040
and the plumbing chase
walls were soaking wet.

00:12:41.040 --> 00:12:43.660
So, the plumbing in
the middle of the core

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:46.780
of the building is
leaking, it's like 30 years

00:12:46.780 --> 00:12:50.910
of not fixing the pipes right,
it's a bad problem at home,

00:12:50.910 --> 00:12:54.700
it's a bad problem when you
have a big library like this.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:57.540
So, the Georgian National
Center for Disease Control

00:12:57.540 --> 00:12:59.840
and Public Health
sampled the air

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:04.480
and counted the colony forming
units in these Petri dishes,

00:13:04.480 --> 00:13:06.000
they did lots of testing.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.620
The primary fungi
were Aspergillus

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:11.720
and the bacteria was nocardia.

00:13:11.720 --> 00:13:15.200
Their findings though indicated
that and this is a quote,

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:17.270
the number of colony
forming units

00:13:17.270 --> 00:13:20.980
in the library does
not pose a health risk.

00:13:20.980 --> 00:13:24.430
I was kind of surprised, in
the US we'd shut the building

00:13:24.430 --> 00:13:27.670
down right, no question
shut it down.

00:13:27.670 --> 00:13:32.050
And yet, this is kind of the
response that you might get

00:13:32.050 --> 00:13:34.960
if there's actually not
a way to deal with this

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:38.580
and everybody agrees what
can we do, we can do nothing,

00:13:38.580 --> 00:13:40.570
we have to accept this.

00:13:40.570 --> 00:13:43.480
So, I kept running into things
that were a little peculiar

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:47.300
in my orientation, but
it was a little scary

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:50.770
because in fact the library
is the testing center

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:52.990
for the university, there
were about 2,000 people

00:13:52.990 --> 00:13:55.580
in the building a day and
I talked to some people

00:13:55.580 --> 00:13:58.780
and they got, they had
gotten sick or were sick

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:00.680
and they were worried.

00:14:00.680 --> 00:14:05.460
So, I met with the
library's administration,

00:14:05.460 --> 00:14:09.290
this is Zurab again
back in Georgia

00:14:09.290 --> 00:14:12.580
and I expressed my concerns
about the health issues

00:14:12.580 --> 00:14:15.400
and agreed to help diagnose
the problem, try and look

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:18.480
for the source of water
and to define a protocol

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:20.300
that would allow them to
recover the rare books

00:14:20.300 --> 00:14:22.640
because in fact the books
looked pretty good except

00:14:22.640 --> 00:14:25.020
for the outside coating of mold.

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:31.420
And so, Marie and Menana helped
assemble a team of local people

00:14:31.420 --> 00:14:35.090
