that of colleagues was

00:43:34.830 --> 00:43:38.560
that the free water must be
eliminated in the building

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:41.920
and to do that we would
need to construct a gallery

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:44.970
on three sides of the
building to provide a barrier

00:43:44.970 --> 00:43:48.430
between the groundwater
and the basement walls.

00:43:48.430 --> 00:43:52.560
We would need to repair the
culinary water pipes in the core

00:43:52.560 --> 00:43:55.970
of the building and realize
those are running in the walls,

00:43:55.970 --> 00:43:58.540
that may be really difficult.

00:43:58.540 --> 00:44:06.050
And we decided we really needed
to add downspouts to be able

00:44:06.050 --> 00:44:10.260
to move the rainwater away
from the base of the building.

00:44:10.260 --> 00:44:11.560
Everything we could do

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:13.270
to eliminate water
into the building.

00:44:13.270 --> 00:44:17.610
The mold spores need to be
prevented from spreading

00:44:17.610 --> 00:44:19.670
into the rest of the building
while we're trying to deal

00:44:19.670 --> 00:44:22.580
with these really,
really moldy rooms.

00:44:22.580 --> 00:44:26.500
So those rooms need to
be positively ventilated,

00:44:26.500 --> 00:44:30.230
that's kind of a trick because
they're down in a subbasement.

00:44:30.230 --> 00:44:33.710
But what we need to
do is exhaust the air

00:44:33.710 --> 00:44:39.330
from the room while we're
drying it through HEPA filters

00:44:39.330 --> 00:44:42.290
and exhausted to the outside,
not through the building

00:44:42.290 --> 00:44:45.330
or get the hoses to go
through the building.

00:44:45.330 --> 00:44:47.210
So, it's a little
complicated, it's the kind

00:44:47.210 --> 00:44:49.900
of equipment we wouldn't
have lying around.

00:44:49.900 --> 00:44:52.540
But we could bring equipment
in and I talked to people

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:54.920
who are willing to do it.

00:44:54.920 --> 00:44:58.660
So next, the storage rooms
needed to be dehumidified

00:44:58.660 --> 00:45:00.680
and that would dehydrate
the mold

00:45:00.680 --> 00:45:03.760
and once it was dehydrated
it would be inactive

00:45:03.760 --> 00:45:07.740
and so the desiccated mold
could be cleaned simply enough

00:45:07.740 --> 00:45:13.000
by HEPA vacuuming it up, we
could just HEPA vac up the mold

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:16.070
and on the books on the
walls on the shelves.

00:45:16.070 --> 00:45:18.890
Whether we did the books in
the same room or not was open

00:45:18.890 --> 00:45:22.200
to discussion, but we could
even start there just vacuuming

00:45:22.200 --> 00:45:23.500
them up.

00:45:23.500 --> 00:45:25.580
And then the walls
and the shelves needed

00:45:25.580 --> 00:45:27.720
to be washed with
soap and water.

00:45:27.720 --> 00:45:30.090
That was from the CDC
and I was fascinated

00:45:30.090 --> 00:45:32.740
because they're not talking
about the use of chlorine

00:45:32.740 --> 00:45:35.330
at all, soap and water.

00:45:35.330 --> 00:45:37.790
Because in fact adding chlorine

00:45:37.790 --> 00:45:40.800
to the environment
might bother people

00:45:40.800 --> 00:45:43.790
who have already got
sensitivities going on because

00:45:43.790 --> 00:45:45.970
of all that mold and
of course all this has

00:45:45.970 --> 00:45:49.360
to be done wearing personal
protective equipment.

00:45:49.360 --> 00:45:53.370
And afterwards we need to
judiciously aerate the rooms

00:45:53.370 --> 00:45:58.310
and the building, find
a way to create airflow.

00:45:58.310 --> 00:46:00.900
But now a year later I am sorry

00:46:00.900 --> 00:46:05.460
to report mold is
still on the books.

00:46:05.460 --> 00:46:07.740
I've had a report from Georgia

00:46:07.740 --> 00:46:13.400
