00:57:37.930 --> 00:57:41.330
These are 80,000 books,
so it's a slow process

00:57:41.330 --> 00:57:43.700
and they were trying to
vacuum every single page.

00:57:43.700 --> 00:57:45.430
I suggested we focus just

00:57:45.430 --> 00:57:48.730
on the exterior mold
and let it be enough.

00:57:48.730 --> 00:57:50.760
It's a question you
know what's enough.

00:57:50.760 --> 00:57:54.790
But the people in the library
is a really interesting question

00:57:54.790 --> 00:57:59.400
because one person who was
doing digital scanning got sick

00:57:59.400 --> 00:58:01.990
and so he went to the doctor

00:58:01.990 --> 00:58:07.370
and the doctor said you
have a respiratory thing,

00:58:07.370 --> 00:58:10.620
take this whatever
this was, and don't do

00:58:10.620 --> 00:58:12.380
that work for three weeks.

00:58:12.380 --> 00:58:15.480
And so, he came back to work,
but kind of was not working

00:58:15.480 --> 00:58:18.700
and I said well do I mind
if I use you as an example

00:58:18.700 --> 00:58:20.940
to plead the case that there
are health problems here

00:58:20.940 --> 00:58:23.060
and he said oh that'll be fine.

00:58:23.060 --> 00:58:24.710
And then he thought
about it overnight

00:58:24.710 --> 00:58:29.190
and he said tomorrow said no
way, don't do that because

00:58:29.190 --> 00:58:30.490
and he left it at that.

00:58:30.490 --> 00:58:33.870
But others explained to me
that if you put your job

00:58:33.870 --> 00:58:36.100
in jeopardy you might
never get another job

00:58:36.100 --> 00:58:39.320
and that there were young
people caring for their parents

00:58:39.320 --> 00:58:42.160
and their parents at
home were in their 40's

00:58:42.160 --> 00:58:44.010
and they were essentially
retired

00:58:44.010 --> 00:58:46.530
out because there
were limited jobs.

00:58:46.530 --> 00:58:50.460
So, people are not willing to
openly say we have a problem

00:58:50.460 --> 00:58:54.850
because there's consequences so.

00:58:54.850 --> 00:58:56.630
&gt;&gt; Fenella France: We have
a couple more questions

00:58:56.630 --> 00:58:58.430
from offsite, they're
quite long ones.

00:58:58.430 --> 00:58:59.860
Do you want to speak?

00:58:59.860 --> 00:59:01.160
&gt;&gt; Fenella France: Let me just.

00:59:01.160 --> 00:59:02.460
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman:
Yeah, just say it.

00:59:02.460 --> 00:59:03.760
&gt;&gt; Fenella France:
So, one question is,

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:05.930
would there be a problem
from a health standpoint

00:59:05.930 --> 00:59:07.230
for future access

00:59:07.230 --> 00:59:10.780
of the collection post-mold
cleaning due to the scale

00:59:10.780 --> 00:59:13.280
of the problems, so it's
a wee bit supposition.

00:59:13.280 --> 00:59:17.890
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman: Yes, good
for you, that's a great question

00:59:17.890 --> 00:59:22.980
and it enters in an area that we
don't really know definitively

00:59:22.980 --> 00:59:24.580
how to define.

00:59:24.580 --> 00:59:27.930
For cost reasons
it's fair to assume

00:59:27.930 --> 00:59:31.830
that just removing the mold on
the books is probably the extent

00:59:31.830 --> 00:59:33.890
of the treatment that
would be possible.

00:59:33.890 --> 00:59:36.050
One of the hesitations
to doing that

00:59:36.050 --> 00:59:38.190
and then putting the books
back in the storage place

00:59:38.190 --> 00:59:42.950
in the building is it's maybe
not environmentally dry enough

00:59:42.950 --> 00:59:46.730
for us to get away with
just having vacuumed it off.

00:59:46.730 --> 00:59:51.200
But we could monitor them and
we could monitor the Rh in rooms

00:59:51.200 --> 00:59:53.980
that they chose to
house them in.

00:59:53.980 --> 00:59:57.740
And if things were improved
or kept to a minimum,

00:59:57.740 --> 01:00:03.840
basically the number we think of
is below 65% relative humidity,

01:00:03.840 --> 01:00:06.310
we're probably going
to be all right.

01:00:06.310 --> 01:00:10.580
But the question you know
if you're probing me to say

01:00:10.580 --> 01:00:14.990
if a person was really sensitive
to molds and the people who are

01:00:14.990 --> 01:00:19.360
for instance have just had
children, they've given birth,

01:00:19.360 --> 01:00:23.940
they have immune deficiency
problems, they've had surgery,

01:00:23.940 --> 01:00:29.870
they have AIDS, that category of
person tends to get a reaction

01:00:29.870 --> 01:00:32.960
to mold more easily than say me.

01:00:32.960 --> 01:00:36.720
And that being the case, it
would be difficult to say

01:00:36.720 --> 01:00:40.060
that for everyone just having
vacuumed off the mold will

01:00:40.060 --> 01:00:41.360
be enough.

01:00:41.360 --> 01:00:45.280
I think so, however, I feel
pretty good about that saying

01:00:45.280 --> 01:00:48.650
that would be a solution in
most cases, but I'd really

01:00:48.650 --> 01:00:54.080
like to see ventilation, outdoor
air coming into a building

01:00:54.080 --> 01:00:56.300
that had this kind of problem.

01:00:56.300 --> 01:00:58.680
I was involved, if I could
just say, I was involved

01:00:58.680 --> 01:01:03.210
in a different disaster in 1997
at Colorado State University

01:01:03.210 --> 01:01:05.670
and because of that
very thing every book

01:01:05.670 --> 01:01:09.480
that was damaged, it
was 450,000 books.

01:01:09.480 --> 01:01:13.560
Got a little slip inside it that
said this is a copy of a book

01:01:13.560 --> 01:01:16.750
that was in that flood and
so it's like a heads up.

01:01:16.750 --> 01:01:20.160
This space because it was an
entire floor of the building,

01:01:20.160 --> 01:01:24.440
this space in theory is maybe
different and maybe you should.

01:01:24.440 --> 01:01:29.790
I suggested to the university it
would be wise to just post that.

01:01:29.790 --> 01:01:31.220
&gt;&gt; Fenella France:
One more [inaudible].

01:01:31.220 --> 01:01:32.520
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman: Sure.

01:01:32.520 --> 01:01:35.020
&gt;&gt; Fenella France: What
was the interest or buy-in

01:01:35.020 --> 01:01:37.490
for the community to
support the stabilization

01:01:37.490 --> 01:01:43.250
and conservation of
the books on site?

01:01:43.250 --> 01:01:45.090
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman: I don't
think the community generally

01:01:45.090 --> 01:01:47.680
knows about this
book collection,

01:01:47.680 --> 01:01:51.610
so I don't know what the
status of that information is.

01:01:51.610 --> 01:01:54.820
But when I told people of
course everybody is sympathetic

01:01:54.820 --> 01:01:57.400
to the idea that we
should fix this problem.

01:01:57.400 --> 01:02:01.400
But I don't think it was widely
known that there are books

01:02:01.400 --> 01:02:03.570
and certainly not
in that condition.

01:02:03.570 --> 01:02:07.870
And I would think for instance
when the Center for Disease

01:02:07.870 --> 01:02:10.940
and Health from Georgia
got involved

01:02:10.940 --> 01:02:13.620
that they would've been kind of
shocked by things and the fact

01:02:13.620 --> 01:02:17.820
that they weren't makes me think
there's a different standard

01:02:17.820 --> 01:02:21.470
than I'm aware of at play.

01:02:25.680 --> 01:02:27.260
One and two good.

01:02:27.260 --> 01:02:28.670
Hi, hi Nora.

01:02:28.670 --> 01:02:36.750
&gt;&gt; Hi, could you tell us
how you got CDC involved

01:02:36.750 --> 01:02:38.550
and the [inaudible]?

01:02:38.550 --> 01:02:39.850
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman: It's
a wonderful question,

01:02:39.850 --> 01:02:41.150
so Nora [inaudible] asked

01:02:41.150 --> 01:02:46.770
when did I get the CDC
involved, how smart am I.

01:02:46.770 --> 01:02:50.490
The question actually is it's
a really interesting answer.

01:02:50.490 --> 01:02:54.050
I left Georgia on a plane
like some, you know,

01:02:54.050 --> 01:02:55.950
five in the morning
kind of flight

01:02:55.950 --> 01:03:01.690
out of you know small countries
and I was so frustrated,

01:03:01.690 --> 01:03:05.110
I knew we didn't quite get
there and I was desperate.

01:03:05.110 --> 01:03:07.660
And so, I was talking
to my seatmate,

01:03:07.660 --> 01:03:10.920
a woman sat down one seat
over and we talked all the way

01:03:10.920 --> 01:03:13.370
to Germany who was from the CDC.

01:03:13.370 --> 01:03:18.340
You know there is
goodness and mercy

01:03:18.340 --> 01:03:21.100
in the world, but it's hiding.

01:03:21.100 --> 01:03:24.120
But she sat down
and she connected,

01:03:24.120 --> 01:03:26.180
I told her how desperate
the situation was

01:03:26.180 --> 01:03:29.680
and she connected me with people
in Atlanta who connected me

01:03:29.680 --> 01:03:34.040
with specialists in West
Virginia who deal with mold.

01:03:34.040 --> 01:03:37.490
And so, it was by
virtue of serendipity,

01:03:37.490 --> 01:03:40.050
a great research tool.

01:03:41.540 --> 01:03:42.840
Andrew.

01:03:42.840 --> 01:03:44.920
&gt;&gt; Yeah, so I'm thinking
now about the ventilation

01:03:44.920 --> 01:03:46.780
and the shafts to
the king's tomb and.

01:03:46.780 --> 01:03:48.080
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman:
There you go.

01:03:48.080 --> 01:03:50.030
&gt;&gt; And clearly that
was planned out ahead

01:03:50.030 --> 01:03:52.930
of time you know for
whatever reasons.

01:03:52.930 --> 01:03:56.840
Are there anyone that you know

01:03:56.840 --> 01:03:59.290
of [inaudible] planning
these kinds of things

01:03:59.290 --> 01:04:02.910
into future building
designs for libraries,

01:04:02.910 --> 01:04:05.060
for cultural heritage
divisions to say let's put

01:04:05.060 --> 01:04:06.670
in an architectural gallery,

01:04:06.670 --> 01:04:09.930
let's put in an [inaudible]
system that we can hook

01:04:09.930 --> 01:04:14.460
up to any interior space
in the building as we need

01:04:14.460 --> 01:04:16.260
to do this kind of thing?

01:04:16.260 --> 01:04:17.560
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman: So.

01:04:17.560 --> 01:04:20.210
Andrew is asking for
those of you at home,

01:04:20.210 --> 01:04:23.670
you know the king's
ventilation shafts,

01:04:23.670 --> 01:04:29.880
the pyramidal ventilation
shafts is such an ideal use

01:04:29.880 --> 01:04:34.190
of existing technology that
it leaves me stunned frankly.

01:04:34.190 --> 01:04:37.270
And you're observing
that there's a real merit

01:04:37.270 --> 01:04:41.520
in capturing ideas like
that and applying them

01:04:41.520 --> 01:04:45.630
in the present day is
absolutely a theme I have going

01:04:45.630 --> 01:04:46.930
in the back of my head.

01:04:46.930 --> 01:04:48.790
What do we know that
we've forgotten right,

01:04:48.790 --> 01:04:54.780
what as a culture have we like
eliminated for whatever reason

01:04:54.780 --> 01:04:56.610
and simply overlooked
at this point.

01:04:56.610 --> 01:04:59.030
Because when I found
those shafts just looking

01:04:59.030 --> 01:05:01.870
through literature I was
shocked, it was like look

01:05:01.870 --> 01:05:04.460
at what they thought
of back then.

01:05:04.460 --> 01:05:07.060
And Andrew asked are thinking

01:05:07.060 --> 01:05:09.950
about applying those
in modern buildings.

01:05:09.950 --> 01:05:12.770
I don't know enough about
architecture, this is a --

01:05:12.770 --> 01:05:15.430
I'm out of my depth,
but there are people,

01:05:15.430 --> 01:05:18.010
especially planning
conservation environments

01:05:18.010 --> 01:05:20.020
who know an awful
lot about this.

01:05:20.020 --> 01:05:22.500
But what you're leading
to is a very key point

01:05:22.500 --> 01:05:24.720
and then I probably
have to wrap up.

01:05:24.720 --> 01:05:28.060
But the idea that if
we build buildings

01:05:28.060 --> 01:05:29.480
that are hermetically sealed

01:05:29.480 --> 01:05:33.710
because we can do HVAC
control that's great as long

01:05:33.710 --> 01:05:35.360
as it's working and the day

01:05:35.360 --> 01:05:38.540
that it's not working we don't
have a second option right.

01:05:38.540 --> 01:05:41.890
It's a completely sealed system
on purpose, which puts us

01:05:41.890 --> 01:05:46.270
at a huge disadvantage and or
when there's something wrong

01:05:46.270 --> 01:05:48.840
in the building, it's just
a little out of whack.

01:05:48.840 --> 01:05:51.970
Getting to a place that we
could ventilate the book storage

01:05:51.970 --> 01:05:54.570
in Georgia was going to be
difficult, we would have

01:05:54.570 --> 01:05:56.960
to ventilate upstairs and out.

01:05:56.960 --> 01:06:01.320
You'd have to have a mile of the
tubing and or cut a hole right

01:06:01.320 --> 01:06:03.760
through the wall, which I
doubt they were interested

01:06:03.760 --> 01:06:05.280
in doing below-grade.

01:06:05.280 --> 01:06:10.250
So, when we build modern
buildings are we thinking

01:06:10.250 --> 01:06:11.550
this way.

01:06:11.550 --> 01:06:14.190
I think there's a group
of people who are aware

01:06:14.190 --> 01:06:17.310
of this stuff, but we should be
harvesting and I'll leave this

01:06:17.310 --> 01:06:21.430
at the last note, we should
be harvesting the bright ideas

01:06:21.430 --> 01:06:25.020
in every way that we can and
some of them are ancient.

01:06:25.020 --> 01:06:27.110
And to ignore these old ideas

01:06:27.110 --> 01:06:30.420
because they're outdated is
not really paying attention.

01:06:30.420 --> 01:06:33.620
When we get into a fix and
we're desperate for an answer,

01:06:33.620 --> 01:06:36.260
when we start clutching
at straws and we come

01:06:36.260 --> 01:06:39.680
across something like this we
should be talking to each other,

01:06:39.680 --> 01:06:43.090
we should be harvesting
these ideas because it's not

01:06:43.090 --> 01:06:48.680
out of its own time now, it's
still time for us to come

01:06:48.680 --> 01:06:51.370
up with alternatives
and variations

01:06:51.370 --> 01:06:53.910
on the way we're
approaching things.

01:06:53.910 --> 01:06:56.150
&gt;&gt; Can I ask a final question?

01:06:56.150 --> 01:06:57.450
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman: Yes, I
would love one more question.

01:06:57.450 --> 01:06:59.480
&gt;&gt; Just to return to
the university library.

01:06:59.480 --> 01:07:03.340
Obviously, they're operating
on a different reality,

01:07:03.340 --> 01:07:09.570
but despite that were there
any lessons learned for you

01:07:09.570 --> 01:07:10.870
that you could share with us?

01:07:10.870 --> 01:07:16.340
If you had to do it again, would
you do anything differently

01:07:16.340 --> 01:07:20.280
and [inaudible] forward
to the next time

01:07:20.280 --> 01:07:21.580
or are you [inaudible]?

01:07:21.580 --> 01:07:27.620
You know there are going to be
limitations on their reality.

01:07:27.620 --> 01:07:29.600
&gt;&gt; Randy Silverman: Mary Oi
[phonetic] just asked the

01:07:29.600 --> 01:07:33.560
million-dollar question,
what did I learn.

01:07:38.730 --> 01:07:43.960
I approached the problem with a
sense of being able to solve it.

01:07:43.960 --> 01:07:49.730
I was so convinced the answer
was intellectually within grasp

01:07:49.730 --> 01:07:55.600
and I was so knocked off center
by my inability to do that.

01:07:55.600 --> 01:07:56.950
And the thing I would
like to share

01:07:56.950 --> 01:08:00.570
with you is we can
know how to fix it

01:08:00.570 --> 01:08:03.720
and we can still not
be able to fix it.

01:08:03.720 --> 01:08:08.860
It's a terrible position to
be in, it's really terrible

01:08:08.860 --> 01:08:12.330
and you know what it's like
a combination of things.

01:08:12.330 --> 01:08:17.340
But in answer to your question,
I failed pure and simple.

01:08:17.340 --> 01:08:26.480
I don't know that I could
have won, I don't know how.

01:08:26.480 --> 01:08:29.850
I begged the people on
the ground you know six

01:08:29.850 --> 01:08:33.300
and eight months later to tell
me how I could've done better

01:08:33.300 --> 01:08:37.250
and they said you did fine,
you know, what are they going

01:08:37.250 --> 01:08:38.620
to say, they're going
to insult me

01:08:38.620 --> 01:08:40.960
and tell me what an
idiot I am, I doubt it.

01:08:40.960 --> 01:08:45.080
But I have to say I
think they were sincere

01:08:45.080 --> 01:08:47.570
and I think all we
can do is try,

01:08:47.570 --> 01:08:49.910
I think the best
we can do is try.

01:08:49.910 --> 01:08:54.160
And the idea of harvesting
old ideas that still are valid

01:08:54.160 --> 01:08:56.540
or looking more carefully
at things

01:08:56.540 --> 01:08:58.560
that we have rejected
along the way

01:08:58.560 --> 01:09:00.920
so that I can bring
a cheap answer.

01:09:00.920 --> 01:09:03.870
The answer was cheap, if I
could have just found a way

01:09:03.870 --> 01:09:05.170
to do it for free.

01:09:05.170 --> 01:09:08.710
I was conning people into, you
know, goading people into coming

01:09:08.710 --> 01:09:12.440
for nothing if they would just
show up on site and ventilate

01:09:12.440 --> 01:09:15.150
that room appropriately so
it wasn't a health risk,

01:09:15.150 --> 01:09:18.650
I had a man committed to doing
several trips if he had to,

01:09:18.650 --> 01:09:21.370
to work for nothing
to make this better,

01:09:21.370 --> 01:09:24.380
and there was not
money to do that.

01:09:24.380 --> 01:09:32.470
So unfortunately, I'm actually
having to swallow the raw pill

01:09:32.470 --> 01:09:36.740
that it's not possible in
every case to fix these things

01:09:36.740 --> 01:09:41.590
and we all live with failures
in little ways all of the time,

01:09:41.590 --> 01:09:47.700
it's humbling, it's frustrating,
and we can do better.

01:09:47.700 --> 01:09:51.340
I would hate to say, to leave
this on a negative note,

01:09:51.340 --> 01:09:56.110
but optimism is not necessarily
going to be able to fix it.

01:09:56.110 --> 01:09:58.510
So, thank you very much.

01:09:58.510 --> 01:10:07.560
[ Applause ]

